  Cryptography is a science that gives practical purpose to mathematics. The outcome of certain
  mathematical theorems is that they become exponentially harder to reverse, making them potentially
  reliable for securing the world of digital communication. The society has increasingly formed rules
  and governance expectations that for many classes of digital data transmission, unencrypted communication
  is forbidden or strongly discouraged.

  Public Key Encryption algorithms form the foundation of secure communication over insecure channels.
  The security relies on computationally hard mathematical problems -- such as integer factorization
  for RSA or the discrete logarithm problem for Diffie Hellman and Elliptic Curve (ECC)
  which remain infeasible to solve efficiently on classical computers, even with massive resource capacity.
  Computing modular exponentiation in RSA is easy in the forward direction (encryption) but requires
  knowing the private factor or exponents to reverse efficiently (decryption).

  In general, these schemes provide strong security under standard proven mathematics theorems, with no
  known classical attacks breaking the bit-security of RSA or ECC in reasonable time. For symmetric
  primitives like AES-128/256, security often targets 128-bit levels, where brute-force or collision
  attacks are computationally infeasible (2¹²⁸ operations). Also, cryptographic hash functions (SHA-256,
  SHA-3) achieve collision resistance making it extremely hard to find two different input with the same
  hash output, which underpin signatures, integrity checks and key derivation in secure protocols.

  Standardize algorithms (NIST, FIPS, IETF RFCs, IACR) are rigorously vetted for resilience across
  communication protocols channels and data encryption use cases. However, the real implementation of
  these algorithms can break with side-channel attacks (timing, power analysis, cache leaks,
  electromagnetic emissions) that exploits physical leakage during operation like modular
  exponentiation or key generation. These process can reveal bits of private key, exponent or even
  entropy source used in randomness generation. And these cryptographic hardware attacks are only
  possible if any parameter leaks observed because of implementation flaws on the algorithms.

