  Quantum Threat
  Classical cryptography forms the core foundation of modern computing infrastructure. It provides the
  assurance that message, transactions, identities and data flows remain confidential, authentic and
  untampered, all these built on algorithms trusted for decades. From TLS handshakes securing every
  HTTPS connection to digital signature verifying software updates, from end-to-end encrypted chats to
  blockchain consesus -- classical public-key cryptography (RSA, Diffie-Hellman, ECC) is the security
  algorithm that protect integrity of the digital interaction. Only if, its purpose is altered in a way
  to have control over the private communication and data flow within the network.

  Quantum computer threat is the new computing superpower -- one that exploits the very laws of Physics
  to perform certain computations in ways no general-purpose classical computer can ever match. In very
  basic terms, Quantum mechanics tells us that a system can exists in multiple states at the same time --
  this is called superposition. When we measure it, we always get one definite outcome with probability
  determined by how much the system was leaning toward each possibility. The simplest case is a two-state
  system (a qubit), where measurement always gives exactly one of two results never anything in between.
  It's like a mirror that doesn't just reflect a pre-existing body but force reality to choose one version
  of yourself when you look.

  A qubit is the fundamental unit of quantum information. It can be in a superposition of both states
  simultaneously.

  |ψ⟩ = α|0⟩ + β|1⟩

  where α and β are complex numbers (amplitude) and |α|² + |β|² = 1.

  -> Before measurement, the qubit is genuinely 0 and 1 at the same time.
  -> After measurement, superposition collapses and classical bit is returned:
    --> 0 with probability |α|²
    --> 1 with probability |β|²

  Classical computers solves problem sequentially -- one path at a time. A classical register with n bits
  can be in one of 2^n possible states at any moment. To explore all 2^n possibilities, it needs 2^n separate
  operations.

  An n-Qubit register in superposition represents all 2^n possible bit strings simultaneously.
  The entire exponential space is explored in parallel through constructive interference. Measurement
  then collapses everything to one classical outcome -- but if the algorithm is design correctly that
  single outcome contains the solution to the hard problem.


  Lattice Cryptography: A new paradigm shift
  A lattice is an infinite grid of points in very high-dimensional space. While classical cryptography hides
  secrets in 1-dimensional modular arithmetic, lattice cryptography hides them inside the geometry of these
  enormous grids, a structure so rich and high-dimensional that even quantum computers cannot efficiently
  break the underlying hard problems.

  Lattice cryptography hides secrets inside a high-dimensional vector space using a very clever trick: a
  good basis versus a bad basis.

  --> The good basis (short, nearly orthogonal vectors) is published openly.
  --> The bad basis (badly conditioned vectors) is kept completely secret.

  A secret short vector or linear combination is very easy to write down using the bad basis but becomes
  extremely hard to discover when you are only given the good basis. To make the secret even harder to find,
  we deliberately add small random noise to the coordinates. This noise turns the secrets point into something
  that looks completely random to the attacker.


