  To describe the polynomial modelling of lattice vector, its essential to understand the linear transformation
  involving multiplication and addition of all coefficients, which are reduced modulo q. The core idea of
  distinguishing a good basis (public vectors) from bad basis (secret, short/orthogonal vectors) is that
  it must be computationally hard to extract the linear relations or find the short vectors.

  Special Polynomial modelling is done with Affine transformations, which return the complete vector as
  good basis by hiding the bad basis during the transformation phase.

  Structure of Affine transformation:

  V <= A * s + e

  where:
   -> A is the public matrix, generated using rejection sampling from the output of SHAKE128 (or similar
   extendable-output function) to ensure uniform distribution over Z_q^{k x k}, where k is the module
   dimension. The rejection sampler discards coefficient values exceeding >= q, ensuring the accepted
   coefficients are uniformly random in [0, q-1) without further reduction.
   -> s is the secret vector, sampled from a narrow distribution with Centered Binomial Distribution (CBD)
   to keep the coefficients centered around zero.
   -> e is the error/noise vector also sampled from CBD to be small and bounded.

 The Vectors (A, s, e) are generated with n-dimensions by mapping to ring polynomials in
 R_q = Z_q[X]/(Xˆn + 1), making the structure more dense and compact. The dimension n is the determined
 based on the security level required for the particular lattice scheme used to generate the key-pairs.




